07317nam a22011895i 9783110898934DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831108989347 a10.1515/97831108989342doi  a(DE-B1597)56692  a(OCoLC)979636105  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPE2402b.P73 2005 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.44/09417222  aHF 5502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/48939:04aThe Pragmatics of Irish English /ced. by Anne Barron, Klaus P. Schneider.  aReprint 2011 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v1640 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIrish English, while having been the focus of investigations on a variety of linguistic levels, reveals a dearth of research on the pragmatic level. In the present volume, this imbalance is addressed by providing much-needed empirical data on language use in Ireland in the private, official and public spheres and also by examining the use of Irish English as a reflection of socio-cultural norms of interaction. The contributions cover a wide range of pragmatic phenomena and draw on a number of frameworks of analysis. Despite the wide scope of topics and methodologies, a relatively coherent picture of conventions of language use in Ireland emerges. Indirectness and heterogeneity on the formal level are, for instance, shown to be features of Irish English. This volume is the first book-length treatment of the pragmatics of a national variety of English, or any other language. Indeed, it could be considered a first step towards a new discipline, variational pragmatics, at the interface of pragmatics and dialectology. This book is of primary interest to researchers and students in pragmatics, variational linguistics, Irish English, English as Foreign Language (EFL), cross-cultural communication and discourse analysis. Furthermore, the pragmatic descriptions provided will be of practical use in the increasingly important English as Second Language (ESL) context in Ireland. Finally, it is also of relevance to professionals dealing with Ireland and, indeed, to anyone interested in a deeper understanding of Irish culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspectszIreland. 0aEnglish languagexVariationzIreland. 0aEnglish languagezIrelandxDiscourse analysis. 0aEnglish languagezIreland. 0aPragmatics. 4aDialektologie. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aEnglisch /Sprache. 4aPragmatik (Sprache). 4aSprachsoziologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aEnglish /language.  aSociolinguistics.  adialectology.  adiscourse analysis.  apragmatics (language).1 aBarron, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarron, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBinchy, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCacciaguidi-Fahy, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahy, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarr, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKallen, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly-Holmes, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, 